## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern identified: **Timeout enforcement + ThreadAbortException catch + ResetAbort**

Your code has three APIs that don't work in .NET 8:
- `Thread.Abort()` → throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`
- `Thread.ResetAbort()` → throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`
- `catch (ThreadAbortException)` → never fires (abort can't be thrown)

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Work doesn't magically stop** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation is *cooperative*. `Task.Run(work)` will keep running in the background after timeout. If `work` is long-running, refactor it to accept a `CancellationToken` and check it periodically (see below). |
| **Dispose the CTS** | `CancellationTokenSource` leaks timers if not disposed. Always `using`. |
| **`Task.WaitAsync` is .NET 6+** | Available on your target (.NET 8) but not on older runtimes. |
| **Fire-and-forget background work** | The abandoned `Task.Run` can throw unobserved exceptions. Add `task.ContinueWith(t => { /* log t.Exception */ }, TaskContinuationOptions.OnlyOnFaulted)` if needed. |

### If `work` can cooperate (preferred)

Refactor to pass the token through so work actually stops on timeout:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    try
    {
        return Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                   .WaitAsync(cts.Token)
                   .GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller example:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### If `work` is truly uncooperative (can't modify it)

Move it to a **child process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout — that's the only way to forcibly stop uncooperative code in modern .NET. `Thread.Abort` has no equivalent.
